content: he does a great job of showing and explaining what he is doing.  He takes it slow and speaks clearly.  Easy to follow what he is doing.

What's good about this course: You learn loads of different coding in HTML and CSS. You get a basic course with Javascript/Jquery and Bootstrap, which will help you get to know how these work. Santosh thoroughly explains much of everything in great detail so you'll understand it.
What's disappointing about this course: Many things are over-explained, that this course feels like "driving down the highway in a golf cart". (sorry for the massive block of text, but I couldn't figure out how to format this review) Good instructor who covers the topics thoroughly. This program, however, does not seem like a "complete foundation" because two things are missing -- database interaction and context. Any foundation must in some manner consider interactivity as Java programs are not run in a void. They require some sort of user input, which requires some sort of database connectivity. The basic CRUD activities and the Java syntax for SQL queries from within Java are missing. Next, context is missing. All Java programs run with a specific goal in mind--that is to say they solve some problem. The topics presented are concepts only ... syntax, classes, flow, arrays, etc. The coverage is thorough, but as presented, it is out of context. Learning would be easier if all these lectures were geared toward accomplishing some overall goal where the student ended up with a working program that incorporates and illustrates the actual usage of all the concepts. Other basic pieces of information that are missing is that although it is stated in one of the beginning tutorials that we can use one of the other IDEs, this is not true, sort of. For instance, for beginners, cutting and pasting the input of event he "hello" program directly into, say, Netbeans results in an error because evidently Netbeans and Eclipse and Intellij are proprietary and in this case, Netbeans adds a line at the beginning of the code: "package hello;" and if this line is deleted, running the code results in an error. Java itself is a program that is basically operating system independent, so the idea that IDE do not get along, so to speak, is slightly ironic. The fix, Maven or Ant, as I'm discovering, adds a level of complexity that is simply annoying. As this tutorial is sold as a "complete foundation," some sort of discussion involving database connectivity and context as mentioned above plus three additional items would make this class "complete." 1. which IDE is the most robust or easiest or reliable 2) portability of specific IDE code (you can import Netbeans to Intellij but not Intellij to Netbeans (I think) 3) how does one deploy the final Java code (on a pc? on an android phone or tablet?)

All this said, few of the Udemy Java tutorials provide database interactivity or context, and few of them are so complete as to address programming from writing the first line of code through deployment, so among his peers on Udemy's democratized education system, Mr. Boehm has actually done a decent job. He has provided a solid collection of information with examples that I will be able to refer back to as I learn more about programming. His competence, his thoroughness, his friendly manner, and his responsiveness put him and this course at the top of the ranks.

I've completed through lesson 10 and will be completing the other lessons. 

If this is your first Nikon DSLR, this is an awesome course.  Each menu setting is described in detail. Jeremy is willing to provide recommendations on settings and the rationale behind his recommendations for settings.  

The course provides excellent detail on how the camera works in each of the automatic settings: how the aperture priority, speed priority and ISO properties will change and why as well as what processing may be going on in the background. This is new information for me and I've been working with the camera for several years. 

So I expect I will be learning new things about white balance and flash photography based on what I've learned so far. 

The one weak point on the series is the cursory treatment of the semi-automatic settings. I am familiar with the principles of aperture priority and speed priority photography from my days with a film camera (also a  Nikon). 

However, I would have liked a more extended treatment of working with P mode and Manual mode. We did not see screen shots of making changes in manual mode or the how the light meter works to assist in determining parameters. 

Overall, I highly recommend this for new Nikon DSLR owners who want to know what each of those many settings and features does.

I thoroughly enjoyed this course. As an anxious person, I am always looking for ways to help me approach life in a more relaxed and less harried manner. This course gives a lot of easy-to-do exercises to fit into a busy and stressful day. I look forward to incorporating them in my life!

This course gives clear explanations and practical motivations for sessions lasting from 1 to 5 minutes that feel so good to do I want to linger longer to enjoy the sense of relaxation & peace.  It teaches techniques for deep breathing, mental & physical focusing, and a visualization exercise that heightens sensory awareness.  I've used each technique individually to de-stress myself in particular situations, and by doing them all together in the morning I remain more relaxed throughout the day.  The lectures and exercises navigate smoothly and they include audio and visual reinforcements that I refer to regularly for fine-tuning my practice.  After some recent conflicts at work and at home, I practiced lessons I learned from the course and I left each situation feeling more peaceful, joyful and confident than before the conflict occurred.  So now I say to stressful situations, "BRING IT."  I highly recommend this course to anyone who wants to relax during or after feeling stressed out.
